Think of it like a movie. Look up establishing shot, and write that. Plenty of sensory, narration, exposition, whatnot. Pull up a stream of your favorite movie composer (or something that fits the scene), and imagine they're composing for you.

Dialogue can be either fast or slow depending on how it's handled. It should advance the plot, increase the tension between characters speaking, or raise the stakes if the conversation affects someone not present.

Think of sentences like metronome tick, and paragraphs like a riff or musical phrase. Or think about brushes for painting. Some are broad and as wide as your palm. Some are only a few hairs wide at the tip.

To slow down your pacing, you can introduce more detail in your prose, and add more body language in your dialogue. Have your characters ask relevant questions, and bridge between different topics so it seems like the conversation is flowing more naturally. If a scene seems shorter than it should be, either give your characters more to do, or improve the description of what they're doing. It's just the opposite of what you would do if things were moving too slowly.
For the formatting? Compare the way your paragraphs are broken up to https://archiveofourown.org/works/32093365/chapters/79506259.
See how there's a full line break between every paragraph here? Having visible breaks gives the eyes space to rest, and makes the piece less fatiguing to read.

>For the formatting?
Just so you're aware, that's what someone like me now calls web formatting, among any number of other names. Some are not polite when you see it in places it shouldn't be.
It's the default in technical books as well for a very obvious reason. You wouldn't digest a programming manual as easily as if it were set in unindented fiction-style paragraphs that have no extra space between the paragraphs.
Part of the reason unindented lines work on the web is a screen could have twice the line length as a hardcover book.

I've found the indented style creeping in self-published fiction. It does not improve the end product.
